ludes many eastern and northern [[Houston, Texas|Houston]] suburbs. Poe is a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], and was the first Republican to represent this particular district.\n\nIn November 2017, Poe announced that he would retire from [[United States Congress|Congress]] at the end of his current term, and not seek re-election in [[United States House of Representatives elections in Texas, 2018|2018]].<ref>{{cite tweet |last=Poe |first=Ted |author-link= |user=JudgeTedPoe |number=928045037367283712 |date=November 7, 2017 |title=Dear Neighbors |script-title= |trans-title= |language= |retweet= |link=https://twitter.com/JudgeTedPoe/status/928045037367283712 |access-date=November 7, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Marcos |first=Christina |date=November 7, 2017 |title=Texas GOP lawmaker won't seek reelection |url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/359239-texas-gop-lawmaker-wont-seek-reelection |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |location=Washington, D.C. |access-date=November 7, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nPoe was born in [[Temple, Texas|Temple]] in [[Bell County, Texas|Bell County]], [[Texas]], but attended [[Spring Woods High School]] in Houston. Poe resides in [[Humble, Texas|Humble]], Texas. He graduated in 1970, with a degree in [[political science]] from [[Abilene Christian University]] in [[Abilene, Texas|Abilene]], Texas; he was his class president. In 1973, he graduated with a [[Juris Doctor]] degree from the [[University of Houston Law Center]]. He participated in the school's honor society. From 1970 to 1976, he served in the [[United States Air Force]] Reserve's C-130 Unit at Houston's [[Ellington Air Force Base]].\n\n==Judicial career==\nAfter serving as a chief felony prosecutor in [[Harris County, Texas|Harris County]] (Houston) for eight years, Poe was appointed a felony court judge in Harris County in 1981, becoming one of the youngest judges in the state. In this position, he gained national prominence for his unusual criminal sentences that included ordering thieves to carry signs in front of stores from which they stole.<ref name=tanenbaum-slut>{{cite book|author=[[Leora Tanenbaum]]|title=Slut!: growing up female with a bad reputation|year=1999|publisher=Perennial|location=New York|isbn=0060957409|page=19|edition=1st}}</ref> However, in at least one case, Poe amended the sentence afterwards without notifying the victim's family.<ref>{{cite web|first=Sarah|last=Fenske|url=http://www.houstonpress.com/2004-10-07/news/after-oprah/|title=After Oprah |publisher=HoustonPress|date=October 7, 2004|accessdate=July 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Elections to United States Congress==\nIn November 2004, Poe ran for the U.S. House in the 2nd District.  The district had previously been the 9th, represented by four-term [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[Nick Lampson]].  However, as the result of a controversial [[2003 Texas redistricting|mid-decade redistricting]], the new 2nd was considerably more Republican than the old 9th.  It lost [[Galveston]] and the area around the [[Johnson Space Center]], while picking up several heavily Republican areas around Houston. Poe won 55% of the vote to Lampson's 43%. While Lampson trounced Poe in Beaumont and Port Arthur, Poe swamped Lampson in the Harris County portion of the district.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/ELECTION/2004//pages/results/states/TX/H/02/county.000.html | work=CNN | title=CNN.com Election 2004}}</ref>\n\nPoe made border security a centerpiece of his re-election strategy, calling for \"more [National] Guardsmen on the border front\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rawstory.com/news/2006/Congressman_says_illegal_immigration_has_slowed_0627.html|title=Rep. says illegal immigration slowing on fears of rape, robbery by Guard|publisher=The Raw Story|date=June 27, 2006|accessdate=July 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2006, Poe won a second term with 65.6% of the vote, defeating [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] Gary Binderim, who took 32.7%.<ref name=\"Gaffney\">Spencer Gaffney, [http://blog.chron.com/txpotomac/2010/07/texas-delegation-in-depth-ted-poe-2/amp/ Texas delegation in depth: Ted Poe], ''Houston Chronicle'' (July 2010).</ref>\n\nIn [[United States House of Representatives elections in Texas, 2008|November 2008]], Poe did not face a Democratic challenger in the general election. He defeated [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]] Craig Wolfe, taking 88.9% of the vote to Wolfe's 11.1%.<ref name=\"Gaffney\"/>\n\nPoe announced on November 7, 2017 that he would not seek re-election in [[United States House of Representatives elections, 2018|2018]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Poe|first1=Ted|title=Ted Poe on Twitter|url=https://twitter.com/JudgeTedPoe/status/928045037367283712|publisher=Twitter|accessdate=November 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Committee assignments==\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Committee on Foreign Affairs]]'''\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Europe and Eurasia|Subcommittee on Europe and Eurasia]]\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Terrorism, Nonproliferation, and Trade|Subcommittee on Terrorism, Nonproliferation, and Trade]] (Chairman)\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations|Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations]] (Vice Chair)\n* '''[[United States House Committee on the Judiciary|Committee on the Judiciary]]'''\n** [[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on Intellectual Property, Competition, and the Internet|Subcommittee on Intellectual Property, Competition, and the Internet]]\n** [[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on Crime, Terrorism, and Homeland Security|Subcommittee on Crime, Terrorism, and Homeland Security]]\n** [[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on Immigration Policy and Enforcement|Subcommittee on Immigration Policy and Enforcement]]\n\nIn addition to Poe's committee assignments, he is the founder and co-chair of the Congressional Victim's Rights Caucus.<ref>{{cite web|title=Victim's Rights Caucus|work=Congressional Victim's Rights Caucus|publisher=United States House of Representatives|url=http://vrc.poe.house.gov/|accessdate=January 26, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Inside the Beltway: Miss Jones|first=John|last=McCaslin|work=Washington Times|date=January 11, 2008|url=http://washingtontimes.com/news/2008/jan/11/inside-the-beltway-45966661/}}</ref> Since 2012, he has been the head of the Congressional [[Serbia]]n Caucus.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics.php?yyyy=2012&mm=07&dd=17&nav_id=81316 |title=Serbian caucus in U.S. Congress has new chairman |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date=July 17, 2012 |work=[[B92]] |publisher= |accessdate=June 21, 2014}}</ref> He is also a member of the [[Republican Study Committee]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|author=|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov/|format=|publisher=Republican Study Committee|date=|accessdate=January 2, 2018}}</ref> the [[Congressional Immigration Reform Caucus]], the [[Congressional Immigration Reform Caucus]], the [[Tea Party Caucus]], the [[House Baltic Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=http://housebalticcaucus.webs.com/members|format=|publisher=House Baltic Caucus|date=|accessdate=February 21, 2018}}</ref> and the [[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Members|author=|url=https://royce.house.gov/internationalconservation/members.html|publisher=U.S. House of Representatives International Conservation Caucus |date=|accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\n[[File:Ted Poe Tea Party April 2009.jpg|300px|thumb|right|Ted Poe speaking at a [[Tea Party movement|Tea Party]] in Texas in 2009]]\n\n===Taxes===\nPoe is a signer of [[Americans for Tax Reform]]'s [[Taxpayer Protection Pledge]].<ref name=\"ATR\">{{cite web|title=The Taxpayer Protection Pledge Signers 112th Congressional List|url=http://s3.amazonaws.com/atrfiles/files/files/091411-federalpledgesigners.pdf|publisher=Americans for Tax Reform|accessdate=November 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Abortion===\nPoe received a 0 rating from the [[abortion rights]] group [[NARAL]] in 2007 and a rating of 100 from the [[National Right to Life Committee]] in 2007\u20132008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.votesmart.org/issue_rating_category.php?can_id=49198|title=Ted Poe's Special Interest Group Ratings|publisher=Project Vote Smart|accessdate=July 10, 2012}}</ref> He also voted for the Prohibiting Federal Funding of Abortion Services amendment on November 7, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.votesmart.org/voting_category.php?can_id=49198|title=Ted Poe's Voting Records|publisher=Project Vote Smart|accessdate=July 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Fiscal policy===\nIn 2008, the National Taxpayers Union, an organization that supports \"lower taxes and smaller government\", gave Poe the grade B+, and in 2007 received a rating of 90 from the group Americans for Tax Reform, an organization that advocates \"taxes [that] are simpler, [and] flatter\".<ref name=\"VoteSmart.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.votesmart.org/issue_rating_category.php?can_id=49198&type=category&category=10&go.x=12&go.y=11|title=Ted Poe's Special Interest Group Ratings|publisher=Project Vote Smart|accessdate=July 10, 2012}}</ref> Poe voted against the 2009 Economic Stimulus Package (HR 1) and the 2010 Concurrent Budget Resolution (S. Con. Res. 13).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.votesmart.org/voting_category.php?can_id=49198&type=category&category=10&go.x=4&go.y=13|title=Ted Poe's Voting Records|publisher=Project Vote Smart|accessdate=July 10, 2012}}</ref> The [[Club for Growth]] PAC gave him a power ranking of 85.85%.<ref name=\"VoteSmart.org\"/>\n\n===Healthcare===\nPoe favors repealing the Affordable Care Act (Obamacare).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/political-courage-test/49198/ted-poe/|title=The Voter's Self Defense System|website=Vote Smart|language=en-US|access-date=March 26, 2017}}</ref> Poe does not support what he calls \"government-run health care\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.votesmart.org/speech_detail.php?sc_id=507678&keyword=&phrase=&contain=|title=Public Statements|publisher=Project Vote Smart|accessdate=July 10, 2012}}</ref> Poe voted \"Nay\" on the Health Care and Insurance Law Amendments bill on November 7, 2009.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.votesmart.org/voting_category.php?can_id=49198&type=category&category=38&go.x=10&go.y=12|title=Ted Poe's Voting Records|publisher=Project Vote Smart|accessdate=July 10, 2012}}</ref> In 2008, Poe voted for the Medicare Bill (HR 6331).<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> Poe supports healthcare reform that would \"Allow insurance to be purchased across state lines, provide for a safety net for catastrophic injury or illness\u2026and allow for a health savings account\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.votesmart.org/speech_detail.php?sc_id=503637&keyword=health+reform&phrase=&contain=|title=Public Statements|publisher=Project Vote Smart|accessdate=July 10, 2012}}</ref> Poe resigned from the [[House Freedom Caucus|Freedom Caucus]] in March 2017, after the Caucus's opposition to the American Health Care Act of 2017 contributed to Speaker Ryan's decision to pull the bill.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/03/26/politics/poe-resigns-freedom-caucus/index.html?adkey=bn|title=First casualty for House Freedom Caucus after health care meltdown|last=CNN|first=Lauren Fox,|work=CNN|access-date=May 16, 2018}}</ref> Poe supported the March 2017 version of the American Health Care Act before its collapse.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2017/03/obamacare-vote-paul-ryan-health-care-ahca-replacement-failure-trump-214947|title=Inside the GOP's Health Care Debacle|work=POLITICO Magazine|access-date=March 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn May 4, 2017, he voted to repeal the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] (Obamacare) and pass the [[American Health Care Act of 2017|American Health Care Act]].<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/politics/ahca-house-vote/|title=How the House voted to pass the GOP health-care bill|website=Washington Post|access-date=May 4, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2017/05/04/health-care-vote-puts-pressure-dozens-vulnerable-gop-reps/101297824/|title=Health care vote puts pressure on dozens of vulnerable GOP reps|work=USA TODAY|access-date=May 4, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Immigration===\nPoe is an advocate of stronger action against [[Illegal immigration in the United States|illegal immigration]] and increased security on the [[Mexico\u2013United States border]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://poe.house.gov/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4284%3Aborder-securityillegal-immigration&catid=105%3Aissues&Itemid=117|title=Border Security/Illegal Immigration|publisher=poe.house.gov|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121030012406/http://poe.house.gov/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4284%3Aborder-securityillegal-immigration&catid=105%3Aissues&Itemid=117|archivedate=October 30, 2012|df=}}</ref> He voted for the [[Secure Fence Act of 2006]] and against the [[DREAM Act]] when it was introduced in 2010.<ref>{{citation|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/key-votes/49198/ted-poe/40/immigration|title=Representative Ted Poe's Voting Records: Immigration|publisher=Project Vote Smart|accessdate=October 26, 2012}}</ref> He opposed the Obama administration's [[Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals]], calling it \"an imperial decree\" that violated immigration law.<ref>{{citation|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/house/233265-gop-blasts-obama-on-house-floor-for-imperial-immigration-decision|first=Pete|last=Kasperowicz|title=GOP blasts Obama on House floor for 'imperial' immigration decision|periodical=The Hill|date=June 18, 2012|accessdate=October 26, 2012}}</ref>\n\nPoe co-sponsored, along with fellow Republican Representative [[Steve King]], the \"Deport Foreign Convicted Criminals Act of 2011\" ({{USBill|112|HR|3256}}), which would require the U.S. government to deny certain visas to citizens of nations that refuse to accept convicted foreign nationals that the U.S. is seeking to deport. If passed, the law would mandate visa denials to nationals of 153 nations worldwide. Poe's bill was opposed by the [[American Immigration Lawyers Association]], which noted that the bill would block visas issued to citizens of American allies, including [[Israel]], [[United Kingdom|Britain]], and [[Canada]]. The bill was also criticized by Democratic Representative [[Jerrold Nadler]] of New York, who called it \"the most stupid bill I've ever seen\" and stated it would wipe out the U.S. tourism industry.<ref>Reid Pillifant, [http://www.politico.com/states/new-york/city-hall/story/2011/11/jerry-nadler-on-the-stupidest-bill-hes-ever-seen-000000 Jerry Nadler on the stupidest bill he's ever seen], ''Politico'' (November 23, 2011).</ref>\n\n===Human trafficking===\nPoe introduced the [[Justice for Victims of Trafficking Act of 2013]] and the [[Justice for Victims of Trafficking Act of 2015]], a bill to combat [[human trafficking]].<ref name=SwartsellNov18>{{cite news|last=Swartsell|first=Nick|title=John Cornyn to file bill to combat human trafficking|url=http://trailblazersblog.dallasnews.com/2013/11/john-cornyn-to-introduce-bill-to-provide-justice-for-sex-trafficking-victims.html/|accessdate=May 19, 2014|newspaper=Dallas News|date=November 18, 2013}}</ref><ref name=MarcosMay16>{{cite news|last=Marcos|first=Cristina|title=Next week: Lawmakers to debate defense and drones|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/scheduling/206363-next-week-defense-authorization-drones|accessdate=May 19, 2014|newspaper=The Hill|date=May 16, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Bynes\">Jesse Bynes, [http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/243519-obama-signs-anti-trafficking-law Obama signs anti-trafficking bill into law], ''The Hill'' (May 29, 2015).</ref> The 2015 bill passed the House in a 420-3 vote and, following a delay, passed the Senate in a 99-0 vote. The bill was signed into law by President [[Barack Obama]] in May 2015.<ref name=\"Bynes\"/>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn 1998, Judge Poe was known for sentences that involved a measure of humiliation, including ordering offenders to shovel manure, a practice which led to the nickname \"The King of Shame.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Turley|first1=Jonathan|title=Shame On You|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/09/17/AR2005091700064.html|website=Washington Post|accessdate=March 8, 2017}}</ref> Poe explained, \"The people I see have too good a self-esteem. I want them to feel guilty about what they've done. I don't want 'em to leave the courthouse having warm fuzzies inside.\" <ref>{{cite web|last1=Shatzkin|first1=Kate|title=Judges Are Resorting to Shame in Sentencing Criminals|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1998/apr/26/news/mn-43159|website=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=March 8, 2017}}</ref> Poe's \"public notice\" sentences included ordering a drunk driver to stand outside a bar, wearing a sign that said \"I killed two people while driving drunk.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Murphy|first1=Dean E.|title=The Nation; Justice as a Morality Play That Ends With Shame|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/06/03/weekinreview/the-nation-justice-as-a-morality-play-that-ends-with-shame.html|website=The New York Times|accessdate=March 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAs a state judge, in November 2002, Poe ruled that he would permit the [[PBS]] documentary show ''[[Frontline (US TV series)|Frontline]]'' to videotape jury deliberations of a capital murder case.<ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C03E3DA1F39F935A15752C1A9649C8B63 \"Inviting TV Into Jury Room in a Capital Case\"], Adam Liptak, November 26, 2002, [[The New York Times]]</ref> There was considerable concern that this would affect the result of the trial, possibly by skewing the composition of the jury, and the decision was appealed by [[Harris County, Texas|Harris County]] prosecuters.<ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B03EED61638F934A15752C1A9649C8B63 \"The 13th Juror\"] (editorial), November 27, 2002, ''[[The New York Times]]''</ref><ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9A07E3DF1E31F935A25752C0A9659C8B63 \"Texas Court to Rule on Videotaping of Jury\"], Adam Liptak, January 16, 2003, [[The New York Times]]</ref> The [[Texas Court of Criminal Appeals]], the state's highest criminal appellate court, ruled against Poe's decision and prohibited the videotaping.<ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D02E4DD173AF930A25751C0A9659C8B63 \"Bid to Tape Deliberations By Texas Jury Is Rejected\"], Adam Liptak, February 13, 2003, [[The New York Times]]</ref>\n\nOn May 7, 2007, while speaking on the floor of the house, Poe used a quote from Civil War Confederate General [[Nathan Bedford Forrest]] when describing the [[military strategy]] that Poe felt the United States should have followed in [[Iraq]]. Forrest's maxim was to: \"Git thar furstest with the mostest.\" The controversy lies in the personal history of General Forrest. He was the Confederate Commander during the [[Battle of Fort Pillow|Fort Pillow massacre]] in which the wholesale murder of surrendering Union troops, especially black soldiers, has drawn permanent infamy.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/fortpillowmassac00unit_0/fortpillowmassac00unit_0_djvu.txt Fort Pillow Massacre], 38th Congress, House of Representatives, Report No. 65, May 6, 1964. Retrieved June 13, 2016.</ref> After his military duty was over, he became the first Grand Wizard of the [[Ku Klux Klan]] (though soon after called for the Klan to disband).\n[[File:Ted Poe 2009.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Poe speaking in 2009]]\nOn June 7, 2009, Poe signed on as a co-sponsor of [[H.R. 1503]], the bill introduced as a reaction to [[conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]] which claimed that [[U.S. President]] [[Barack Obama]] is [[Barack Obama citizenship conspiracy theories|not a natural born U.S. citizen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/z?d111:HR01503:@@@P|title=H.R.1503: Amend the Federal Election Campaign Act to require a birth certificate|publisher=THOMAS|date=|accessdate=July 10, 2012}}</ref> On July 23, 2009, he appeared on [[CNN]]'s ''[[Lou Dobbs Tonight]]'' in which he claimed that Certifications of Live Birth issued by Hawaii State Department of Health cannot be used to obtain a U.S. passport, which is untrue.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0907/23/ldt.01.html|title=Lou Dobbs Tonight: July 23, 2009 transcript|publisher=CNN|date=July 23, 2009|accessdate=July 10, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hawaii.gov/health/vital-records/vital-records/vital_records.html|title=How to Apply for Certified Copies of Vital Records|publisher=State of Hawaii|accessdate=July 10, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.factcheck.org/elections-2008/born_in_the_usa.html|title=Born in the U.S.A.: The truth about Obama's birth certificate|publisher=FactCheck.org|date=November 1, 2008|accessdate=July 10, 2012}}</ref> His support of H.R. 1503 and public advocacy for it earned him a negative editorial in the ''[[Houston Chronicle]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/editorial/6553893.html|title=Birth wrongs: Conspiracy theories on Obama beyond silly|publisher=Houston Chronicle|date=July 29, 2009|accessdate=July 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2011, [[AlterNet]] reported that Poe, along with [[John Culberson]] and [[Michael McCaul]], was attempting to remove the right of deceased soldiers' families to choose which prayers, if any, were to be read at a soldier's funeral.<ref name=rock/><ref name=alternet/> The three politicians were said to be attempting to impose Christian ceremonies on the military funerals of everybody who has served in the military, regardless of whether or not the deceased was Christian and with or without the consent of the family of the deceased. The three politicians stated their demands were a response to [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs|Veterans Affairs]] (VA) banning Christian prayers at military funerals. The VA, however, asserted that this claim was \"blatantly false\" and that VA respects a family's \"rights to pray however they choose at our national cemeteries\".<ref name=rock>{{cite web|url=http://rockbeyondbelief.com/2011/08/05/tx-congressmen-to-force-christian-prayer-over-my-dead-body/|title=TX Congressmen to force Christian prayer over my dead body.|author=Griffith, Justin|date=August 5, 2011|work=rockbeyondbelief.com|publisher=|accessdate=September 6, 2011}}</ref><ref name=alternet>{{cite web|url=http://www.alternet.org/world/152143/texas_legislators_and_christian_groups_fight_to_insert_god_into_vets'_funerals_--_against_families'_wishes/?page=entire|title=Texas Legislators and Christian Groups Fight to Insert God Into Vets' Funerals \u2013 Against Families' Wishes|author=DiBrance, Alex|date=August 23, 2011|work=[[AlterNet]]|accessdate=September 6, 2011}}</ref>\n\nPoe was elected to his seventh term in the House in the [[general election]] held on November 8, 2016. With 168,692 votes (60.6 percent), he defeated the Democrat Pat Bryan, who received 100,231 ballots (36 percent). Two other candidates held the remaining 3.35 percent of the votes cast.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elections.sos.state.tx.us/elchist319_state.htm|title=Election Results|date=November 8, 2016|publisher=Texas Secretary of State|accessdate=December 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPoe and his wife, Carol, have four children (Kim, Kara, Kurt, and Kellee).<ref>{{cite web|title=About Ted|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/49198/ted-poe#.VIoBpJAZ5yA}}</ref>\n\nPoe announced on July 13, 2016, that he had recently been diagnosed with [[leukemia]] and would be seeking treatment at [[University of Texas MD Anderson Cancer Center]].<ref name=leukemia>{{cite web|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2016/07/13/ted-poe-diagnosed-cancer/ |title=Diagnosed With Leukemia, U.S. Rep. Ted Poe Ready to Fight |author=Livingston, Abby |date=July 13, 2016 |newspaper=Texas Tribune |accessdate=July 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nPoe was interviewed about his controversial [[public humiliation]] practices while still a Texas district judge by [[Jon Ronson]] for Ronson's 2015 book, ''[[So You've Been Publicly Shamed]]''.<ref name=\"Verdict\">{{cite web | url=https://verdict.justia.com/2015/03/20/is-shame-necessary-how-about-public-shaming | title=Is Shame Necessary? How About Public Shaming? | publisher=Justia (Verdict Blog) | date=March 20, 2015 | accessdate=April 7, 2015 | author=Dean, John}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portalbar|Biography|Houston|Texas|Politics|Conservatism|Government of the United States|United States Air Force|Christianity}}\n\n{{sisterlinks}}\n* [https://poe.house.gov/home Congressman Ted Poe] official U.S. House site\n* [http://www.tedpoe.com/ Ted Poe for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Texas/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Ted_Poe_%5BR-2%5D}}\n* {{C-SPAN|Ted Poe}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=p000592 | votesmart=49198 | fec=H4TX02108 | congress=ted-poe/1802 }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060529082209/http://www.sourcewatch.org/index.php?title=Ted_Poe Profile] at [[SourceWatch]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060714010815/http://www.joecookprogram.com/archives.html Interview on \"The Joe Cook Program\" in Philadelphia] June 23, 2006\n* {{YouTube|j-5K1vHB27g|Video of Speech praising Nathan Bedford Forrest on the House Floor}} May 7, 2007\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jim Turner (politician)|Jim Turner]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from 